<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-12-01T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-12-01T17:00:00-05:00" n="1109" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1109">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72111/939</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Chargé d’Affaires in Colombia</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HL1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Bogotá</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-12-01T17:00:00-05:00">
                                <hi rend="italic">December 1, 1914, 5 p.m.</hi>
                            </date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received December 2, 3:15 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>Relative to Colombian neutrality. Newspapers publish telegram from
                            Washington reporting statement by officials of the Department to the
                            effect that “The United States will go so far as to permit European
                            nations to send expeditions to force compliance, if it is so deemed
                            necessary.”</p>
                        <p>Minister for Foreign Affairs asks if this is correct. He fears that it
                            may indicate intention to despatch such expeditions which would be
                            entirely undeserved.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_HL1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>